Arithmetic and intermediate Jacobians of some rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds

Alexander Molnar Department of Mathematics and Statistics
Queen’s University
Kingston, Ontario, K7L 3N6 a.molnar@queensu.ca
Abstract.

We construct Calabi-Yau threefolds defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}} via quotients of abelian threefolds, and re-verify the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds in this construction are modular by computing their L-series, without [8] or [12]. We compute the intermediate Jacobians of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds as complex tori, then compute a ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model for the 1-torus given a ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-structure on the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds, and find infinitely many examples and counterexamples for a conjecture of Yui about the relation between the L𝐿L-series of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds and the L𝐿L-series of their intermediate Jacobians.

1. Introduction

Associated to any smooth projective variety, the intermediate Jacobian varieties generalize Jacobian varieties of curves. For X𝑋X an n𝑛n-dimensional complex variety we define the (Griffiths) intermediate Jacobians of X𝑋X to be the varieties

Jk+1​(X):=H2​k+1​(X,ℂ)/(Fk+1​H2​k+1​(X,ℂ)⊕H2​k+1​(X,ℤ))assignsuperscript𝐽𝑘1𝑋superscript𝐻2𝑘1𝑋ℂdirect-sumsuperscript𝐹𝑘1superscript𝐻2𝑘1𝑋ℂsuperscript𝐻2𝑘1𝑋ℤJ^{k+1}(X):=H^{2k+1}(X,{\mathbb{C}})/(F^{k+1}H^{2k+1}(X,{\mathbb{C}})\oplus H^{2k+1}(X,{\mathbb{Z}}))

where the quotient involves only the torsion free part of H2​k+1​(X,ℤ)superscript𝐻2𝑘1𝑋ℤH^{2k+1}(X,{\mathbb{Z}}) and Fk+1superscript𝐹𝑘1F^{k+1} is the (k+1)𝑘1(k+1)-th level in the Hodge filtration, i.e.,

Fk+1​H2​k+1​(X,ℂ)=⨁p+q=2​k+1q<k+1Hp,q​(X).superscript𝐹𝑘1superscript𝐻2𝑘1𝑋ℂsubscriptdirect-sum𝑝𝑞2𝑘1𝑞𝑘1superscript𝐻𝑝𝑞𝑋F^{k+1}H^{2k+1}(X,{\mathbb{C}})=\bigoplus_{\begin{subarray}{c}p+q=2k+1\\ q<k+1\end{subarray}}H^{p,q}(X).

Thus, for a curve C𝐶C, the only intermediate Jacobian is J1​(C)superscript𝐽1𝐶J^{1}(C), which is the Jacobian variety of the curve. We will be interested mostly in Calabi-Yau varieties, so for the one-dimensional case we have elliptic curves which are known to be isomorphic to their (intermediate) Jacobians, and these are all the possibilities. For two dimensional examples one has K3 surfaces which have trivial first and third cohomology, hence no-non-trivial intermediate Jacobians, and so our focus will be with Calabi-Yau threefolds. Here the only non-trivial intermediate Jacobian is

J​(X):=J2​(X)=(H0,3​(X)⊕H1,2​(X))/H3​(X,ℤ).assign𝐽𝑋superscript𝐽2𝑋direct-sumsuperscript𝐻03𝑋superscript𝐻12𝑋superscript𝐻3𝑋ℤJ(X):=J^{2}(X)=(H^{0,3}(X)\oplus H^{1,2}(X))/H^{3}(X,{\mathbb{Z}}).

Not much is known about these varieties, but they are very useful tools. As complex varieties one has e.g., [5] who used the intermediate Jacobian of a cubic threefold to show there exist unirational varieties that are not rational, and [24] where intermediate Jacobians are used to show the Griffiths group of a general member in a family of non-rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds is infinite dimensional. An interest in the physics literature comes from the use of Calabi-Yau varieties in string theory, e.g., in [1], [7] and [17]. As X𝑋X is Kähler we have that the intermediate Jacobian is a complex torus of dimension 1+h1,2​(X)1superscriptℎ12𝑋1+h^{1,2}(X). Thus, when X𝑋X is rigid, J2​(X)superscript𝐽2𝑋J^{2}(X) is a 1-torus, possibly with a canonical structure of an elliptic curve.

The work to date studies the geometry of J​(X)𝐽𝑋J(X), i.e., the complex structure. However, as intermediate Jacobians generalize the classical Jacobian variety of a curve, as well as the Picard varieties and Albanese varieties of any n𝑛n-dimensional varieties, it is natural to ask if one can study arithmetic on all intermediate Jacobians by finding a canonical ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-structure when X𝑋X is defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}. All of our examples of Calabi-Yau threefolds will be defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}, but one can similarly try to associate a canonical K𝐾K-structure for any number field K𝐾K if X𝑋X is defined over K𝐾K instead. We will construct some rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds in which we are able to compute their intermediate Jacobians as complex varieties, and then refine this computation to give a natural ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-structure as well, given a choice of model for the Calabi-Yau threefolds defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}.

Shafarevich conjectures that every variety of CM-type (meaning its Hodge group is abelian) has the L𝐿L-series of a Grossencharacter, a Hecke L𝐿L-series, and Borcea shows that a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold with CM-type has a CM elliptic curve as its intermediate Jacobian, which is well known to have a Hecke L𝐿L-series. Thus, if the conjecture is true, it is a natural question to ask if there is any relation between the associated Grossencharacters of a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold and its intermediate Jacobian. The motivation for the current work is to study a precise conjecture of Yui to this effect.

Conjecture 1 (Yui, [26]).

Let X𝑋X be a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold of CM-type defined over a number field F𝐹F. Then the intermediate Jacobian J2​(X)superscript𝐽2𝑋J^{2}(X) is an elliptic curve with CM by an imaginary quadratic field K𝐾K, and has a model defined over the number field F𝐹F.

If χ𝜒\chi is a Hecke character associated to J2​(X)superscript𝐽2𝑋J^{2}(X) and

L​(J2​(X),s)={L​(χ,s)​L​(χ¯,s)if​K⊂F,L​(χ,s)otherwise,𝐿superscript𝐽2𝑋𝑠cases𝐿𝜒𝑠𝐿¯𝜒𝑠if𝐾𝐹𝐿𝜒𝑠otherwise,L(J^{2}(X),s)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}L(\chi,s)L(\overline{\chi},s)&\text{if}\ K\subset F,\\ L(\chi,s)&\text{otherwise,}\end{array}\right.

then

L​(X,s)={L​(χ3,s)​L​(χ¯3,s)if​K⊂F,L​(χ3,s)otherwise.𝐿𝑋𝑠cases𝐿superscript𝜒3𝑠𝐿superscript¯𝜒3𝑠if𝐾𝐹𝐿superscript𝜒3𝑠otherwise.L(X,s)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}L(\chi^{3},s)L(\overline{\chi}^{3},s)&\text{if}\ K\subset F,\\ L(\chi^{3},s)&\text{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.

Consequently, X𝑋X is modular.

We will show that many of our rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds of CM-type satisfy this conjecture, but not all. In particular, we will show that if one of our examples, X𝑋X, satisfies the conjecture, then all quadratic twists of X𝑋X satisfy the conjecture, while all non-quadratic twists of X𝑋X do not. After this we generalize our construction to Calabi-Yau n𝑛n-folds and show that for infinitely many n𝑛n satisfying a congruence with the order of the CM automorphisms we have the natural generalization of the conjecture is true. Similarly, for infinitely many n𝑛n the conjecture will not be true because of the CM twists on the varieties.

We start by constructing our varieties and studying their geometry over ℂℂ{\mathbb{C}}. We use a generalized Borcea construction of Calabi-Yau threefolds using (finite) quotients of products of elliptic curves, and determine which quotients give rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds. We then choose a ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-structure for the Calabi-Yau threefolds, via the underlying elliptic curves, and compute their respective L𝐿L-series. Once this is done we compute the intermediate Jacobians as complex tori, and then over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}, via the choice of ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-structure given on the threefolds. We are then able to compare the L𝐿L-series of the intermediate Jacobians and their respective threefolds and check the conjecture.

Our construction also gives rise to non-rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds, which we leave to future work [15], as the intermediate Jacobians are no longer elliptic curves, and the arithmetic of 2-tori and 4-tori is more complicated. Moreover, the question of modularity (automorphy) is nowhere near as resolved, as [8] and [12] no longer apply.

2. Construction of threefolds

Remark.

All mirror pairs except (1,73)173(1,73) can be found in the toric construction of [14], while the last mirror can be found in [2] which constructs Calabi-Yau varieties and their mirrors via conifold transitions. It would be interesting to see if there is a relationship between the intermediate Jacobians in a mirror pair.

3. Modularity

We say a variety X/ℚ𝑋ℚX/{\mathbb{Q}} of dimension d𝑑d is modular if its L𝐿L-series, the L𝐿L-series of the d𝑑d-th ℓℓ\ell-adic cohomology of X𝑋X, is the L𝐿L-series of a newform f=∑an​qn𝑓subscript𝑎𝑛superscript𝑞𝑛f=\sum a_{n}q^{n} of weight d+1𝑑1d+1 on Γ0​(N)subscriptΓ0𝑁\Gamma_{0}(N) for some N𝑁N. Here, a newform is taken to mean a normalized (a1=1subscript𝑎11a_{1}=1) eigenform on Γ0​(N)subscriptΓ0𝑁\Gamma_{0}(N) that is not induced by a cusp form on Γ0​(N′)subscriptΓ0superscript𝑁′\Gamma_{0}(N^{\prime}) for any smaller N′∣Nconditionalsuperscript𝑁′𝑁N^{\prime}\mid N. We say the newform f𝑓f has CM by a quadratic number field K𝐾K if an=φK​(n)​ansubscript𝑎𝑛subscript𝜑𝐾𝑛subscript𝑎𝑛a_{n}=\varphi_{K}(n)a_{n} for almost all n𝑛n, where φKsubscript𝜑𝐾\varphi_{K} is the non-trivial Dirichlet character associated to K𝐾K.

All rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}} are modular by [8] or [12], in particular, all of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds in our construction. One can use Serre’s conjecture to determine the associated newforms (hence L𝐿L-series) as the (now proven) conjecture gives a bound on the level of the newform. It is a small product of powers of the primes of bad reduction of the corresponding threefold. However, this method is not practical when there are large primes of bad reduction, as one must construct spaces of cusp forms of high level and search for the correct newform. We will be able to avoid this by computing the L𝐿L-series without the a priori knowledge of modularity, via a method shown to us by Hector Pasten [18], taking advantage of the elliptic curves/abelian threefold structure of our varieties.

We will need one lemma about Hecke characters of imaginary quadratic number fields before approaching this computation, and for the convenience of the reader, we recall some basic facts about these characters. For any quadratic imaginary number field K𝐾K with ideal 𝔪𝔪{\mathfrak{m}} we say a Hecke character χ𝜒\chi of modulus 𝔪𝔪{\mathfrak{m}} and infinity type c𝑐c is a homomorphism

4. Intermediate Jacobians

In this section we compute the intermediate Jacobians of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds described above. For each rigid Calabi-Yau threefold X𝑋X, its intermediate Jacobian simply

J​(X)=H0,3​(X)/H3​(X,ℤ),𝐽𝑋superscript𝐻03𝑋superscript𝐻3𝑋ℤJ(X)=H^{0,3}(X)/H^{3}(X,{\mathbb{Z}}),

a 1-torus. The method we use to compute these tori is to recognize how to reconstruct the torus structure of an elliptic curve from a analogous quotient of its cohomology groups, extending Roan’s work on Kummer threefolds in [21]. We then analyze the construction of the intermediate Jacobians as complex varieties more closely to determine a ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model in each case.

Remark.

As our ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model for J​(Y4​(D2))𝐽subscript𝑌4superscript𝐷2J(Y_{4}(D^{2})) requires choosing a scaled basis for the complex cohomology, one could argue the result above is ad hoc and simply designed to get the result we desire. However, note that having fixed the underlying elliptic curves on the threefold, we have fixed the integral cohomology classes, and so the period relation cannot be scaled by a non-integer. The uniformization theorem tells us integral twists require non-integral homotheties, and so our period relation cannot be scaled in some way to give another model for J​(Y4​(D2))𝐽subscript𝑌4superscript𝐷2J(Y_{4}(D^{2})), defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}. Hence, while the particular model for J​(Y4​(D2))𝐽subscript𝑌4superscript𝐷2J(Y_{4}(D^{2})) depends on the choice of basis, the natural ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model does not. Now, as any CM elliptic curve has a model defined over a number field, our ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model seems the best fit.

4.4. Roan’s special automorphism

As E3subscript𝐸3E_{3} and E4subscript𝐸4E_{4} are the only elliptic curves with the CM automorphisms, we cannot naively continue in an attempt to construct rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds of CM-type using a triple product of the other CM elliptic curves and a triple product of CM actions. Nevertheless, one may ask if all CM newforms of weight 4 with rational coefficients can be realized as the newform associated to a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}. If Yui’s conjecture is true, this is not possible. E.g., suppose there is a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold of CM-type, defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}, with associated modular form having level 232superscript23223^{2} (see [22]). Then the intermediate Jacobian would be an elliptic curve defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}, with CM by ℚ​(−23)ℚ23{\mathbb{Q}}(\sqrt{-23}), but of course no such curves exist.

If the conjecture is true, we can weaken our hopes to asking if every CM elliptic curve defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}} is the ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model for the intermediate Jacobian of a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold, of CM-type, defined over ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}. 5. Remarks on special values of L𝐿L-functions

With a ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model of the intermediate Jacobians associated to any ℚℚ{\mathbb{Q}}-model of our rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds via the conjecture, we are able to define the L𝐿L-functions of the respective varieties and investigate their behaviour in their critical strips.
